The Joint Humanitarian Response for Ebola (JRE) addresses the direct humanitarian needs as well as the indirect consequences related to the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. This 9-month joint programme is implemented in the 3 most affected countries, namely Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea, by 7 Dutch NGOs. Together they work towards four objectives. The first two objectives aim at stopping theEbola outbreak and treating the Ebola infected by identifying and tracing people with Ebola, supporting safe burials, providing health care for patients, promoting clinical hygiene in treatment and health care facilities, and ensuring medical care for health workers. Besides the direct health crises, the Ebola outbreak is having a wider impact on the general health system, security situation,economy and livelihoods in all affected countries. Therefore, the organisations also aim to ensure essential services and preserve stability by providing food and social safety net support, ensuring safe access to water and sanitation facilities, providing psycho-social support, increasing public awareness and social mobilization.

The World Citizens Panel is an impact measurement method developed by Oxfam. The focus is on measuring changes in peoples' lives bycombining quantitative research (impact surveys) among Oxfam#s  target population and a control group with qualitative research (stories of change) and thus give participants a voice.  This project will help Oxfam understand how programmes can be improved, as well as contribute to the public debate on effectiveness of development cooperation.  The project builds on a previous startup workshopin which Oxfam agreed on how to undertake this impact survey.  Thereafter a reflection workshop was held to discuss the main findings based on the data collected among 14 partners with more than 4.000 respondents. The next step is to train partners in collectingqualitative stories of change in order to deepen the insights gained from the impact survey and get a better understanding of the changes that happened in people's lives. An impact report will be published, based on the surveysand the stories of change. For more information on the background of the World Citizens Panel, preliminary results and publications, please visit www.worldcitizenspanel.com.

The Joint Response for Somalia is a project funded by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs through the Dutch Relief Alliance. Oxfam Novib is leading a consortium that consists of Dorcas, SOS Children#s Villages, World Vision and Oxfam Novib. The proposed projectaims to address the HRP objectives of providing life-saving and life-sustaining integrated, multi-sectoral assistance to reduce acute humanitarian need for communities affected by the drought and protracted conflict. The (revised) Humanitarian Response Plan, dated July 2018, states there are currently 5,4 mln people in need. The locations and sectors for project implementation are to be determined in a planning workshop taking place on 24 and 25 October, with representatives from the participating consortium members and local partners.
It is part of the SEEDS GROW PROGRAMME.

The CRAFT project has been developed through collaboration between Oxfam Novib and partners with a view to achieve accountable, fair and pro-poor tax systems. Within this project the partners (in particular in Nigeria, Mali, Senegal, Ghana, Egypt and Bangladesh) are trained to improve their research and advocacy skills and they meet each other twice a year during strategy meetings. So far theproject has accumulated a vast amount of research and policy documents and has supported public and private policy work. More information about the project can be found on: www.maketaxfair.netCRAFT - Tax Justice

This is a five-year program, initially known as #DOEL#, implemented by five national level organizations i.e. BRAC, HASAB, FPAB, CAMPE and BNPS. The culture in Bangladesh is very conservative and sensitive about SRHR issues and does not allow open sharing of information on these issues. This #silence# prevents the people, particularly adolescents, to access to the information, supports and services which contribute to the persistence of high prevalence of early marriage and maternal-child mortality. The project seeks to break this #silence#. The objective of this project is to improve the sexual and reproductive health rights (SRHR) status of adolescents (60% girls) through creating increased access to information and services. The project adopts a comprehensive approach combining, campaigning, peer-education, teaching-learning approaches to achieve the program objectives. Initially, the project is covering twelve sub-districts of six (06) districts targeting to reach 45,000 grade 6 to 10 students and 300,000 out of School youths to educate them on SRHR as well as increase the awareness of at least 5% of the parents of adolescents on SRHR issues. The project also targets to mobilize 15 leading media journalists to advocate the SRHR issues as well as sensitize 50 potentially opposing political leaders, who are confronted with the Muslim teachings on SRHR and safe behaviour, and motivated to support formal and informal SRHR curricula. The program will be extended its coverage more upon receiving funding supports from external sources.

Oxfam Novib is one of the 17 national affiliates of the Oxfam International Confederation. It started life in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994.  Working together in confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education forall, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies.  Oxfam established this country office to support local organizations and projects.  Through this local office Oxfam Novib directly contributes towards this projects implementation.

Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy.
